<paragraph id="016C1165FF87395FE9CCC518FC7E5970" blockId="41.[406,1257,466,582]" box="[765,897,555,582]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">
<figureCitation id="99E80DE0FF87395FE9CCC518FC7E5970" box="[765,897,555,582]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="40.[227,270,1753,1779]" captionTargetBox="[227,1437,603,1722]" captionTargetId="figure-226@40.[227,1437,603,1722]" captionTargetPageId="40" captionText="Fig. 13. Fish otoliths from the US middle and upper Eocene. A–C. “Conger” websteri (Frost, 1933), Piney Point F., Pamunkey River, 1 km E of Eanes property, Virginia (IRSNB P 10014–10016). D. “Osteoglossum” aff. rhomboidalis (Stinton, 1977), “Stone City beds”, Stone City Bluff, Brazos River, sample 2 from bed P, Texas (P 10017). E–F. Neoopisthopterus weltoni sp. nov. E. Landrum M., Crockett, Texas, holotype (IRSNB P 10018). F. “Stone City beds”, Stone City Bluff, Brazos River, bed I, Texas, paratype (IRSNB P 10019). G. Sardinops sp., Landrum M., Crockett, Texas (IRSNB P 10020). H. Clupeidae indet., Landrum M., Crockett, Texas (IRSNB P 10021). I–J. Plotosus sp., Wheelock M., Little Brazos River, confluence with Brazos River, Texas (P 10022–10023). 1 = ventral view; 2 = inner view; 3 = anterior view. Scale bars = 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6484382" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6484382/files/figure.png" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Fig. 13E–F</figureCitation>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="49C942EEFF87395FEBD2C545FC5659C2" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="016C1165FF87395FEBD2C545FEA359A6" blockId="41.[227,348,630,656]" box="[227,348,630,656]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">
<heading id="5A24A609FF87395FEBD2C545FEA359A6" bold="true" box="[227,348,630,656]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" reason="3">
<emphasis id="33A7CD77FF87395FEBD2C545FEA359A6" bold="true" box="[227,348,630,656]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="016C1165FF87395FEBD2C59DFC5659C2" blockId="41.[227,1436,686,757]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">OL/OH = 1.64–1.68, OsL/CaL = 1.00–1.07. Otoliths trapezoid, thin, with large rostrum. Sulcus wide and shallow. Ostium opens widely. Cauda straight and wide.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="49C942EEFF87395FEBD2C416FBEF5892" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="016C1165FF87395FEBD2C416FE955809" blockId="41.[227,362,805,831]" box="[227,362,805,831]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">
<heading id="5A24A609FF87395FEBD2C416FE955809" bold="true" box="[227,362,805,831]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" reason="3">
<emphasis id="33A7CD77FF87395FEBD2C416FE955809" bold="true" box="[227,362,805,831]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Etymology</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="016C1165FF87395FEBD2C46EFBEF5892" blockId="41.[227,1436,861,932]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">
This species is dedicated to Bruce Welton, who provided us a lot of otoliths, and as an appreciation of his extensive work on the fossil shark teeth from the Gulf 
<collectingRegion id="C317DF87FF87395FE8BFC4B9FC2E5892" box="[910,977,906,932]" country="New Zealand" name="West Coast" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Coast</collectingRegion>
area.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
