<paragraph id="016C1165FF87395FEBD2C16BFE8B5D44" blockId="41.[227,372,1624,1650]" box="[227,372,1624,1650]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">
<heading id="5A24A609FF87395FEBD2C16BFE8B5D44" bold="true" box="[227,372,1624,1650]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" reason="3">
<emphasis id="33A7CD77FF87395FEBD2C16BFE8B5D44" bold="true" box="[227,372,1624,1650]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Description</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="016C1165FF87395FEBD2C1A3FDAA5339" blockId="41.[226,1437,1680,2063]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">
This species is characterized by rectangular to trapezoid otoliths. The dorsal rim is more or less straight. The posterior rim is gently curved, forming rounded junctions with the dorsal and ventral rims. The ventral rim varies, which partly resulted from its preservation status; it is slightly irregular in the 
<typeStatus id="DE68AFC7FF87395FEBD2C025FEB55C06" box="[227,330,1814,1840]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">holotype</typeStatus>
(
<figureCitation id="99E80DE0FF87395FEA6BC025FE3C5C06" box="[346,451,1814,1840]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="40.[227,270,1753,1779]" captionTargetBox="[227,1437,603,1722]" captionTargetId="figure-226@40.[227,1437,603,1722]" captionTargetPageId="40" captionText="Fig. 13. Fish otoliths from the US middle and upper Eocene. A–C. “Conger” websteri (Frost, 1933), Piney Point F., Pamunkey River, 1 km E of Eanes property, Virginia (IRSNB P 10014–10016). D. “Osteoglossum” aff. rhomboidalis (Stinton, 1977), “Stone City beds”, Stone City Bluff, Brazos River, sample 2 from bed P, Texas (P 10017). E–F. Neoopisthopterus weltoni sp. nov. E. Landrum M., Crockett, Texas, holotype (IRSNB P 10018). F. “Stone City beds”, Stone City Bluff, Brazos River, bed I, Texas, paratype (IRSNB P 10019). G. Sardinops sp., Landrum M., Crockett, Texas (IRSNB P 10020). H. Clupeidae indet., Landrum M., Crockett, Texas (IRSNB P 10021). I–J. Plotosus sp., Wheelock M., Little Brazos River, confluence with Brazos River, Texas (P 10022–10023). 1 = ventral view; 2 = inner view; 3 = anterior view. Scale bars = 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6484382" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6484382/files/figure.png" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Fig. 13E</figureCitation>
), but largely undulated in the figured 
<typeStatus id="DE68AFC7FF87395FE84CC025FC195C06" box="[893,998,1814,1840]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">paratype</typeStatus>
. The anterior portion is characterized by a large, robust, and extended rostrum with a small but notable excisura. The otoliths are nearly flat on both faces. The sulcus is not deep but very wide and clearly divided into ostium and cauda. No collicula are visible. The ostial crista inferior curves somewhat upwards anteriorly and the ostium opens widely antero-dorsally. The cauda is straight and wide. At its posterior end, the cristae are indistinct. The dorsal area is somewhat hollowed out.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="49C942EEFF84395CEBD2C61DFBF05ACD" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="016C1165FF84395CEBD2C61DFEAA5A7E" blockId="42.[227,341,302,328]" box="[227,341,302,328]" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">
<heading id="5A24A609FF84395CEBD2C61DFEAA5A7E" bold="true" box="[227,341,302,328]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" reason="3">
<emphasis id="33A7CD77FF84395CEBD2C61DFEAA5A7E" bold="true" box="[227,341,302,328]" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">Remarks</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="016C1165FF84395CEBD2C650FBF05ACD" blockId="42.[226,1436,355,507]" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">
<taxonomicName id="C6D36AE6FF84395CEBD2C650FDF15A4B" authority="Lin &amp; Nolf &amp; Steurbaut, 2022" authorityName="Lin &amp; Nolf &amp; Steurbaut" authorityYear="2022" box="[227,526,355,381]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pristigasteridae" genus="Neoopisthopterus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Clupeiformes" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="weltoni" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="33A7CD77FF84395CEBD2C650FDF15A4B" box="[227,526,355,381]" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">Neoopisthopterus weltoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="2894700CFF84395CE924C657FD905A48" box="[533,623,356,382]" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
is a rare species; only 
<specimenCount id="17D5DAECFF84395CE844C650FBCF5A4B" box="[885,1072,355,381]" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" type="generic">three specimens</specimenCount>
are currently known: two from the Cook Mountain Formation and one from the “Stone City beds”, both in 
<collectingRegion id="C317DF87FF84395CEF68C6BEFB5E5A91" box="[1113,1185,397,423]" country="United States of America" name="Texas" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">Texas</collectingRegion>
. The above diagnosis allows us to assign this new species to the Recent genus 
<taxonomicName id="C6D36AE6FF84395CE8B3C685FBAE5AE6" authorityName="Hildebrand" authorityYear="1948" box="[898,1105,438,464]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pristigasteridae" genus="Neoopisthopterus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Clupeiformes" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="33A7CD77FF84395CE8B3C685FBAE5AE6" box="[898,1105,438,464]" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">Neoopisthopterus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see 
<bibRefCitation id="65426C94FF84395CEFA1C685FA675AE7" author="Nolf &amp; Aguilera" box="[1168,1432,438,465]" firstAuthor="Nolf" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" pagination="237 - 262" refId="ref55899" refString="Nolf D. &amp; Aguilera O. 1998. Fish otoliths from the Cantaure Formation (early Miocene of Venezuela). Bulletin de l'Institut royal des Sciences naturelles de Belgique, Sciences de la Terre 68: 237 - 262." type="journal article" year="1998">Nolf &amp; Aguilera 1998</bibRefCitation>
: pl. 2 fig. 11 for an illustration of an otolith of the Recent 
<taxonomicName id="C6D36AE6FF84395CE84CC6D2FC015ACC" baseAuthorityName="Hildebrand" baseAuthorityYear="1946" box="[893,1022,481,506]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pristigasteridae" genus="Neoopisthopterus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Clupeiformes" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="tropicus">
<emphasis id="33A7CD77FF84395CE84CC6D2FC015ACC" box="[893,1022,481,506]" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">N. tropicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
